---
import Layout from "@/layouts/main.astro"
import { Button } from "@/components/ui/button"
---

<Layout>
  <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto mt-8 border-x-[3px] border-b-[3px] border-foreground p-6 sm:p-10 mb-16 relative">
    
    <!-- Top Label -->
    <div class="absolute -top-[18px] left-1/2 -translate-x-1/2 bg-background px-4 font-bold uppercase tracking-widest text-lg border-[3px] border-foreground">
      Dear Julian
    </div>

    <div class="text-center mb-12 mt-6 max-w-2xl mx-auto">
       <p class="text-lg italic text-foreground/80">
         Straight talk and honest advice for modern relationships. Have a question? Write to Julian.
       </p>
    </div>

    <div class="space-y-12">
      <!-- Q1: Red Flags -->
      <article>
        <h3 class="font-bold text-2xl mb-2 leading-tight">"They keep canceling plans at the last minute."</h3>
        <p class="mb-4 text-foreground/90 leading-relaxed">
          <span class="font-bold uppercase text-sm tracking-wide mr-2">Dear Julian,</span> 
          I've been seeing someone for a month. Twice now, they have canceled dinner an hour beforehand with vague excuses. When we do hang out, it's great, but this unreliability is exhausting. Am I overreacting, or is this a major red flag?
        </p>
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-right mb-6">— Waiting in Washington</p>
        
        <div class="pl-6 border-l-4 border-foreground py-2 text-foreground/90 italic">
          <span class="font-bold uppercase text-sm tracking-wide block mb-2 not-italic">Dear Waiting,</span>
          Red flags look just like regular flags when you are wearing rose-colored glasses. Chronic flakiness early in a relationship isn't just rude—it's an indicator of how much they value your time. The standard for the first few months should be their absolute best behavior. If this is their best, you don't want to stick around for their average. Stop holding the time open for them and start prioritizing people who show up.
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- Q2: Boundaries -->
      <hr class="border-t-2 border-foreground/30 border-dashed" />
      <article>
        <h3 class="font-bold text-2xl mb-2 leading-tight">"My roommate keeps using my expensive shampoo."</h3>
        <p class="mb-4 text-foreground/90 leading-relaxed">
          <span class="font-bold uppercase text-sm tracking-wide mr-2">Dear Julian,</span>
          I share a bathroom with my best friend. She knows how expensive my hair products are, yet I see the bottles depleting rapidly. I don't want to start a fight or ruin the friendship, but I can't afford to keep subsidizing her haircare. How do I stop this without sounding stingy?
        </p>
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-right mb-6">— Drained in Denver</p>
        
        <div class="pl-6 border-l-4 border-foreground py-2 text-foreground/90 italic">
          <span class="font-bold uppercase text-sm tracking-wide block mb-2 not-italic">Dear Drained,</span>
          Boundaries are the immune system of a friendship. When you fail to set them to 'keep the peace', you actually just create a silent war of resentment. You don't need a grand confrontation. The next time you see her, cheerfully say, "Hey! I've noticed my shampoo is going super fast. Let's make sure we keep our shower products separate from now on." If she takes offense, the friendship was built on convenience, not respect. Keep the shampoo in your room if you must.
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- Q3: Conflicts -->
      <hr class="border-t-2 border-foreground/30 border-dashed" />
      <article>
        <h3 class="font-bold text-2xl mb-2 leading-tight">"We argue about the exact same things for hours."</h3>
        <p class="mb-4 text-foreground/90 leading-relaxed">
          <span class="font-bold uppercase text-sm tracking-wide mr-2">Dear Julian,</span>
          When my partner and I fight, we end up going in circles. A discussion about chores will somehow turn into a debate about something he said three years ago. It goes on until 2 AM, and we wake up exhausted with nothing resolved. How do we break the loop? 
        </p>
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-right mb-6">— Exhausted in Elgin</p>
        
        <div class="pl-6 border-l-4 border-foreground py-2 text-foreground/90 italic">
          <span class="font-bold uppercase text-sm tracking-wide block mb-2 not-italic">Dear Exhausted,</span>
          You are fighting to win, not fighting to resolve. This is classic 'kitchen sinking'—throwing every past grievance into the current argument. The fix requires discipline. Establish a "one topic at a time" rule. If a past issue gets dragged in, the other person gently flags it. More importantly, implement a hard stop. Nothing productive happens after midnight. Agree to table the debate and sleep. You'll be amazed how trivial the argument feels in the morning light.
        </div>
      </article>

    </div>

    <!-- Submission CTA -->
    <div class="mt-16 text-center border-t-[3px] border-foreground pt-8">
      <h4 class="font-bold uppercase tracking-widest text-xl mb-4">Have a dilemma?</h4>
      <Button className="font-bold uppercase tracking-widest bg-foreground text-background hover:bg-foreground/80 px-8 py-6 rounded-none border-2 border-foreground">Write to Julian</Button>
    </div>
    
  </div>
</Layout>
